# Square
  `market_visits++`
  > Brindlewick's market is a ring of dripping awnings, bright apples, wet boots, and sharper eyes.
  > Tarps sag under rainwater until sellers jab them upward with broom handles, sending silver sheets crashing into the mud.
  > `has_crate` The crate from the cloak seller knocks against your knee with every step. Whatever is inside answers each jolt with a nervous little clink.
  + -> [Visit the cloak seller](#.CloakSeller)
  + -> [Speak to the woman with the blue scarf](#.BlueScarf)
  + -> [Slip into the alley](#.Alley)
  + -> [Return to the village inn](/main.saga#Village)

## CloakSeller
  `met_cloak_seller := true`
  ![Cloak Seller](/assets/images/cloak_seller.png)
  > A narrow man shakes rainwater from a row of heavy cloaks. Each cloak hangs from its peg like a patient, hooded witness.
  > He smiles without showing teeth, which somehow makes the smile feel more expensive.
  > `has_cloak` He nods approvingly at the cloak you bought from him, as if pleased to see his merchandise surviving the argument with the weather.
  + `coin >= 2` -> [Buy a dry cloak](#.BuyCloak)
  + -> [Ask for work](#.OddJob)
  + -> [Browse and leave](#Square)

### BuyCloak
  `coin := coin - 2`
  `has_cloak := true`
  > The cloak smells of cedar and sheep oil. It is ugly, warm, and yours.
  > When you fasten it, rain begins striking your shoulders with a frustrated, muffled patter.
  -> [..]

### OddJob
  >> [Cloak Seller](/characters.saga#CloakSeller) Carry this crate to Mira in the alley. She pays if she likes your face.
  >> If she doesn't, bring the crate back and I'll pretend I never trusted you with it.
  + *-> [Take the crate](#.TakeCrate)
  + -> [Decline politely](#..)

#### TakeCrate
  `has_crate := true`
  > The crate clinks with bottles wrapped in straw. A paper tag tied to the handle reads MIRA in blocky ink.
  > It is not heavy at first, but it has the stubborn balance of something that intends to become heavy later.
  -> [Square.Alley]

## BlueScarf
  `met_blue_scarf := true`
  ![Blue Scarf](/assets/images/blue_scarf.png)
  > The woman with the blue scarf watches the crowd reflected in a brass mirror.
  > She never looks directly at you until you are close enough to see the whole market bent in the mirror's curved face.
  >> `trust_blue_scarf` [Blue Scarf](/characters.saga#BlueScarf) You came back. Good.
  >> `trust_blue_scarf` That means either you listened, or Brindlewick failed to scare you off. Both are rarer than they should be.
  + `visited_start` -> [Mention the crescent letter](#.LetterTalk)
  + -> [Ask about the old watchtower](#.WatchtowerTalk)
  + -> [Leave her to her mirror](#Square)

### LetterTalk
  `trust_blue_scarf := true`
  > She folds the mirror shut. The market vanishes from its face with a soft click.
  > For the first time, she looks at you directly, and the noise of the square seems to step backward.
  >> [Blue Scarf](/characters.saga#BlueScarf) Then you are already late. Find the archivist's mark beneath the tower.
  >> The tower is only the lid. Whatever matters in Brindlewick is always under something else.
  + *-> [Ask what the mark looks like](#..MarkDescription)
  + -> [Return to the market](#..)

### MarkDescription
  `knows_mark := true`
  >> [Blue Scarf](/characters.saga#BlueScarf) A bell inside a closed eye.
  >> If you see it, knock twice and wait.
  >> Do not knock three times. Three is an invitation, and you do not know what might answer.
  -> [..]

### WatchtowerTalk
  >> [Blue Scarf](/characters.saga#BlueScarf) The tower was built over a well.
  >> Everything important in Brindlewick is underneath something else.
  >> People forget that. The ground does not.
  + -> [Thank her](#..)

## Alley
  > The alley behind the market smells of rain, onions, and lamp smoke.
  > Water runs down the center channel carrying apple peels, candle stubs, and one playing card with all its faces washed blank.
  > `has_crate` Mira's crate grows heavier the longer you carry it, as if the bottles are drinking in the damp.
  + `has_crate` -> [Deliver the crate to Mira](#.Mira)
  + -> [Visit the locksmith](#.Locksmith)
  + -> [Return to the cloak seller](#..CloakSeller)
  + -> [Return to the square](#Square)

### Mira
  `met_mira := true`
  ![Mira](/assets/images/mira.png)
  `has_crate := false`
  `coin := coin + 3`
  > Mira counts the bottles and presses three old coins into your hand.
  > She does not hurry. Each coin lands in your palm after its own small judgment.
  >> [Mira](/characters.saga#Mira) Counted fair. Tell him I liked your face well enough.
  >> And tell him the blue bottle was short last time. If he acts surprised, charge him for the acting.
  -> [..]

### Locksmith
  `met_locksmith := true`
  ![Locksmith](/assets/images/locksmith.png)
  > The locksmith's stall is hardly wider than its door. Keys hang from the ceiling like iron fruit.
  > Every time the wind moves, the keys touch and whisper in a language of teeth and tumblers.
  > `lantern_lit` The blue flame in your lantern makes every key cast two shadows. The locksmith watches the second shadows more carefully than the first.
  + `old_key` -> [Show him the blackened key](#.BlackKey)
  + `coin >= 1` -> [Buy lamp oil](#.LampOil)
  + -> [Leave the stall](#..)

#### BlackKey
  `lower_door_hint := true`
  > He whistles, low and unwilling.
  >> [Locksmith](/characters.saga#Locksmith) That opens a lock that hates daylight. Oil it before you turn it.
  >> And if it turns too easily, stop. Some doors open wide because they are hungry.
  -> [..]

#### LampOil
  `coin := coin - 1`
  `lantern_lit := true`
  > He fills your lantern and lights it with a blue spark from his thumbnail.
  > The flame steadies at once, small and intent, as though it has been waiting for you to catch up.
  -> [..]
